## 6. Database Schema (Core Tables)

```sql
-- Companies (multi-tenant from day 1)
companies (id, name, address, gstin, state, whatsapp_number, owner_phone, created_at)

-- Employees
employees (id, company_id, name, role, base_salary, phone_number, bank_account,
           pf_account, face_encoding FLOAT[], is_active, joined_at)

-- Attendance logs
attendance_logs (id, employee_id, date, punch_in TIMESTAMPTZ, punch_out TIMESTAMPTZ,
                 hours_worked FLOAT, overtime_hours FLOAT, status ENUM, source ENUM, created_at)
-- status: present | absent | half_day | holiday
-- source: whatsapp | qr_code | manual

-- Payroll runs
payroll_runs (id, company_id, month, year, status ENUM, total_payout, run_at, created_by)
-- status: draft | approved | paid

-- Payroll line items (one per employee per run)
payroll_line_items (id, run_id, employee_id, basic, overtime_pay, leave_deduction,
                    festival_bonus, gross, pf_employee, esic_employee, professional_tax,
                    total_deductions, net_pay, snapshot JSONB)
-- snapshot = full calculation breakdown stored as JSON for audit trail

-- Compliance config
compliance_rules (id, company_id, state, rule_type, config JSONB)
```

---

## 7. Payroll Engine API (engine/ package)

The engine is a **pure Python package** with zero web dependencies. It must be independently testable.

```python
# engine/salary.py — core interface

from dataclasses import dataclass

@dataclass
class EmployeeInput:
    employee_id: str
    base_salary: float
    working_days: int          # days present (from attendance)
    overtime_hours: float      # total OT hours this month
    unpaid_leave_days: int
    festival_bonus: bool
    state: str                 # for professional tax slab lookup

@dataclass
class PayrollResult:
    basic: float
    overtime_pay: float
    leave_deduction: float
    festival_bonus: float
    gross: float
    pf_employee: float
    esic_employee: float
    professional_tax: float
    total_deductions: float
    net_pay: float
    employer_pf: float
    employer_esic: float
    cost_to_company: float
    breakdown: dict            # full audit trail

def calculate(input: EmployeeInput, rules: ComplianceRules) -> PayrollResult:
    ...
```

**Key calculation constants:**
- Standard working days per month: 26
- OT multiplier: 2× daily rate per OT day (configurable)
- Festival bonus: 8.33% of basic (1/12th of annual bonus = statutory minimum)
- PF threshold: applicable on salary ≤ ₹15,000 basic (statutory), but applied to full basic here
- ESIC threshold: applicable if gross ≤ ₹21,000/month

---

## 8. Phase-Wise Build Roadmap

### Phase 1 — Core Payroll Engine (Weeks 1–2)
**Goal:** Be able to calculate correct salary for any employee with variable inputs.

Tasks:
- [ ] Set up repo structure, Docker Compose (FastAPI + PostgreSQL + Redis)
- [ ] Create all DB models + Alembic migrations
- [ ] Build `engine/salary.py` — full calculation with all components
- [ ] Build `engine/compliance/india.py` — PF, ESIC, Professional Tax rules
- [ ] Write YAML rule files for Maharashtra, Karnataka, Delhi
- [ ] Unit test engine with 20+ test cases (edge cases: ESIC threshold, OT = 0, no bonus, etc.)
- [ ] `POST /api/payroll/calculate` — accepts employee inputs, returns breakdown

**Done when:** Running `pytest engine/` passes 100%. You can POST employee data and get correct net pay back.

---

### Phase 2 — Employee Management + Manual Attendance (Weeks 3–4)
**Goal:** Owner can set up employees and manually mark attendance via web UI.

Tasks:
- [ ] `POST /api/companies` — create company
- [ ] `POST /api/employees` — add employee (name, role, base salary, phone, bank)
- [ ] `GET /api/employees` — list all
- [ ] `POST /api/attendance/manual` — owner marks attendance for date + employee
- [ ] `GET /api/attendance/{month}` — monthly view
- [ ] Next.js web app: employee list page, attendance grid (calendar view per employee)
- [ ] shadcn/ui data table for employee management
- [ ] Run payroll manually: select month → review auto-calculated salaries → approve

**Done when:** Suresh can add 10 employees and manually run payroll for November. Correct net pay shown.

---

### Phase 3 — Payslip PDF + Bank Export (Week 5)
**Goal:** Generate professional payslip PDF and NEFT-ready CSV.

Tasks:
- [ ] Design payslip HTML template (WeasyPrint renders HTML→PDF)
- [ ] Payslip sections: company header, employee info, earnings table, deductions table, employer contributions, net pay in words, compliance footer
- [ ] `GET /api/payroll/{run_id}/payslip/{employee_id}` → returns PDF
- [ ] `GET /api/payroll/{run_id}/bank-export` → returns CSV
- [ ] Bank CSV format: `Employee Name, Account Number, IFSC, Amount, Remarks`
- [ ] Payslip PDF sent via email (SendGrid free tier) or WhatsApp

**Done when:** A payslip PDF for Ramesh matches the design spec exactly. Bank CSV opens in Excel with correct columns.

---

### Phase 4 — WhatsApp Bot + Face Check-In (Weeks 6–8)
**Goal:** Zero manual attendance marking — employees check in via WhatsApp selfie.

Tasks:
- [ ] Set up Meta WhatsApp Business API, get webhook URL verified
- [ ] `POST /api/webhooks/whatsapp` — webhook receiver
- [ ] Download image from Meta media URL → extract face encoding (`face_recognition`)
- [ ] Employee onboarding flow: owner sends "register [employee_name]" → bot guides face photo upload
- [ ] Store face encoding in `employees.face_encoding`
- [ ] Check-in flow: face match → time window check → duplicate check → write AttendanceLog
- [ ] Check-out flow: same face match → calculate hours → flag OT
- [ ] Poor lighting detection: check mean pixel brightness, reply with helpful message
- [ ] Daily summary Celery task → WhatsApp message to owner at 8PM
- [ ] `GET /api/attendance/today` → dashboard view showing live check-in status

**Done when:** Ramesh sends a selfie on WhatsApp. System correctly logs check-in. Owner receives daily summary. Payroll for the month auto-populates from attendance.

---

### Phase 5 — Dashboard + Polish (Week 9–10)
**Goal:** Clean owner-facing dashboard. Production-ready.

Tasks:
- [ ] Dashboard: total payout this month, attendance rate, pending approvals, overtime alerts
- [ ] Attendance heatmap (employee × day grid, colour-coded)
- [ ] Payroll run history with audit trail
- [ ] Employee self-service: employee can WhatsApp "myslip" to get their payslip PDF
- [ ] Multi-company support (one deployment, multiple shops)
- [ ] README with one-command Docker setup
- [ ] GitHub Actions: lint + test on every PR

**Done when:** A non-technical person can run `docker-compose up` and set up their company in under 10 minutes.

---

### Phase 6 (v2) — QR Code Attendance
**Goal:** Add QR as a second attendance method. No new backend logic — just a new source.

Tasks:
- [ ] Generate unique daily QR per employee (URL: `/checkin?emp=EMP001&token=DAILY_HASH&date=20241104`)
- [ ] Daily token = HMAC(employee_id + date, secret_key) — expires at midnight
- [ ] `GET /checkin` → mobile-friendly page → records GPS + timestamp → writes AttendanceLog with `source=qr_code`
- [ ] Morning WhatsApp blast: send each employee their daily QR image
- [ ] Owner can view check-in source (WhatsApp vs QR) in attendance log

